%S A395116 1,1,1,9,11,13,29,401,271,4481,3389,4113,657359,528641,1891,83249729,
%T A395116 162403313,1358821,1685790049,247664201,20263993,618617349593,
%U A395116 1468784073439,3358592353,1291172911351,75399798733793,61961671279,1308956012064121,443692071804856879
%N A395116 Odd part of the field norm of a regularized mock theta limit at a primitive 2n-th root of unity.
%C A395116 The terms were computed by exact arithmetic in Q(zeta_(2n)), not by numerical approximation.
%C A395116 Empirical observation, verified for 1 <= n <= 29: v_2(N_n) = 2*phi(2n), where phi is Euler's totient function.
%C A395116 Empirical observation, verified for odd n, 3 <= n <= 29: a(n) == 1 mod n.
%C A395116 Empirical observation, verified for odd n, 1 <= n <= 29: every rational prime L dividing a(n) satisfies L == 1 mod 2*n.
%C A395116 For even n the preceding splitting pattern need not hold; for example, 3 divides a(4) = 9 and a(12) = 4113 = 3^2 * 457.
%C A395116 For odd n, Q(zeta_(2n)) = Q(zeta_n), so the even-root and odd-root algebraic integers lie in the same cyclotomic field.
%H A395116 Kathrin Bringmann and Larry Rolen, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/s40687-015-0035-8">Radial limits of mock theta functions</a>, Research in the Mathematical Sciences, Vol. 2, No. 1 (2015), Article 17.
%H A395116 Amanda Folsom, Ken Ono, and Robert C. Rhoades, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/fmp.2013.3">Mock theta functions and quantum modular forms</a>, Forum of Mathematics, Pi, Vol. 1, Cambridge University Press (2013), e2.
%H A395116 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="https://github.com/archmageirvine/joeis/blob/master/src/irvine/oeis/a395/A395116.java">Java program</a> (github)
%F A395116 a(n) = N_n / 2^v_2(N_n) where N_n = abs(Norm_{Q(xi_n)/Q}(L_n(xi_n))), L_n(xi) = -4 * Sum_{r=0..n-1} Product_{j=1..r} (1 + xi^j)^2 * xi^(r+1), and xi_n = exp(Pi*I/n).
%e A395116 For n = 1, xi_1 = -1. We have L_1(-1) = 4, so N_1 = 4 and a(1) = 4/2^2 = 1.
%e A395116 For n = 4, a(4) = 9.
%e A395116 For n = 5, a(5) = 11, and 11 == 1 mod 10.
%e A395116 For n = 7, a(7) = 29, and 29 == 1 mod 14.
%e A395116 For n = 11, a(11) = 3389.
%o A395116 (SageMath)
%o A395116 from sage.all import *
%o A395116 def a(n):
%o A395116     K = CyclotomicField(2*n)
%o A395116     xi = K.gen()
%o A395116     inner = K(0)
%o A395116     poch = K(1)
%o A395116     for r in range(n):
%o A395116         if r > 0:
%o A395116             poch *= 1 + xi^r
%o A395116         inner += poch^2 * xi^(r + 1)
%o A395116     L = -4 * inner
%o A395116     N = ZZ(abs(L.norm(QQ)))
%o A395116     return N // (2**N.valuation(2))
%o A395116 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 30)])
%Y A395116 Cf. A000010, A393567, A394831.
%K A395116 nonn
%O A395116 1,4
%A A395116 _Joesph Daniel Burke III_, May 11 2026
